<doc id="430680" wikidata="Q840594" url="?curid=430680" title="Motive (algebraic geometry)">
<text>In algebraic geometry, motives (or sometimes motifs, following French usage) is a theory proposed by Alexander Grothendieck in the 1960s to unify the vast array of similarly behaved cohomology theories such as singular cohomology, de Rham cohomology, etale cohomology, and crystalline cohomology. Philosophically, a &quot;motif&quot; is the &quot;cohomology essence&quot; of a variety.

In the formulation of Grothendieck for smooth projective varieties, a motive is a triple formula_1, where formula_2 is a smooth projective variety, formula_3 is an idempotent correspondence, and &quot;m&quot; an integer; however, such a triple contains almost no information outside the context of Grothendieck&#x27;s category of pure motives, where a morphism from formula_1 to formula_5 is given by a correspondence of degree formula_6. A more object-focused approach is taken by Pierre Deligne in &quot;Le Groupe Fondamental de la Droite Projective Moins Trois Points&quot;. In that article, a motive is a &quot;system of realisations&quot; – that is, a tuple

:formula_7

consisting of modules

:formula_8

over the rings

:formula_9

respectively, various comparison isomorphisms

:formula_10

between the obvious base changes of these modules, filtrations formula_11, a action formula_12 of the absolute Galois group formula_13 on formula_14 and a &quot;Frobenius&quot; automorphism formula_15 of formula_16. This data is modeled on the cohomologies of a smooth projective formula_17-variety and the structures and compatibilities they admit, and gives an idea about what kind of information is contained in a motive.

== Introduction ==
The theory of motives was originally conjectured as an attempt to unify a rapidly multiplying array of cohomology theories, including Betti cohomology, de Rham cohomology, &quot;l&quot;-adic cohomology, and crystalline cohomology. The general hope is that equations like
* [projective line] = [line] + [point]
* [projective plane] = [plane] + [line] + [point]
can be put on increasingly solid mathematical footing with a deep meaning. Of course, the above equations are already known to be true in many senses, such as in the sense of CW-complex where &quot;+&quot; corresponds to attaching cells, and in the sense of various cohomology theories, where &quot;+&quot; corresponds to the direct sum.

From another viewpoint, motives continue the sequence of generalizations from rational functions on varieties to divisors on varieties to Chow groups of varieties. The generalization happens in more than one direction, since motives can be considered with respect to more types of equivalence than rational equivalence. The admissible equivalences are given by the definition of an adequate equivalence relation.

== Definition of pure motives ==
The category of pure motives often proceeds in three steps. Below we describe the case of Chow motives formula_18, where &quot;k&quot; is any field.

=== First step: category of (degree 0) correspondences, Corr(&quot;k&quot;) ===
The objects of formula_19 are simply smooth projective varieties over &quot;k&quot;. The morphisms are correspondences. They generalize morphisms of varieties formula_20, which can be associated with their graphs in formula_21, to fixed dimensional Chow cycles on formula_21.

It will be useful to describe correspondences of arbitrary degree, although morphisms in formula_19 are correspondences of degree 0. In detail, let &quot;X&quot; and &quot;Y&quot; be smooth projective varieties and consider a decomposition of &quot;X&quot; into connected components:

:formula_24

If formula_25, then the correspondences of degree &quot;r&quot; from &quot;X&quot; to &quot;Y&quot; are

:formula_26

where formula_27 denotes the Chow-cycles of codimension &quot;k&quot;. Correspondences are often denoted using the &quot;⊢&quot;-notation, e.g., formula_28. For any formula_29 and formula_30 their composition is defined by

:formula_31

where the dot denotes the product in the Chow ring (i.e., intersection).

Returning to constructing the category formula_32 notice that the composition of degree 0 correspondences is degree 0. Hence we define morphisms of formula_19 to be degree 0 correspondences.

The following association is a functor (here formula_34 denotes the graph of formula_35):

:formula_36

Just like formula_37 the category formula_19 has direct sums () and tensor products (). It is a preadditive category. The sum of morphisms is defined by

:formula_39

=== Second step: category of pure effective Chow motives, Choweff(&quot;k&quot;)===

The transition to motives is made by taking the pseudo-abelian envelope of formula_19:

:formula_41.

In other words, effective Chow motives are pairs of smooth projective varieties &quot;X&quot; and &quot;idempotent&quot; correspondences α: &quot;X&quot; ⊢ &quot;X&quot;, and morphisms are of a certain type of correspondence:

